To get the most benefit from the new [virtual threads][1] feature in Java 21+, it is suggested to replace `synchronized` blocks / functions with [reentrant locks][2].

This is easy in many cases:

    public synchronized int size() {
		return map.size();
	}

Can be replaced with: 
    
    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    public int size() {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            return map.size();
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }

What about a case where we pass a mutex in?

    public int size() {
		synchronized (mutex) {
			return c.size();
		}
	}

In this case, can we wrap the whole synchronized block in a reentrant lock? Will the following pin the reentrant lock instead of the OS thread? If not, how do we best handle this situation?

    private final Object mutex;
    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    public MyClass(Object mutex) {
        this.mutex = mutex;
    }

    public int size() {
        lock.lock();
        try {
            synchronized (mutex) {
                return c.size();
            }
        } finally {
            lock.unlock();
        }
    }



    


