I would split this pattern into 3 parts. The first row, the middle rows, and the bottom row.

The first row is relatively easy. Just print the numbers from 1 to `num` inclusive.

```
for (int i=1; i&lt;=num; i++){
    System.out.print(i + &quot; &quot;);
}
System.out.println();
```

The middle rows follow a pattern like this:

```
2        num - 1
3        num - 2
4        num - 3
...
num - 3        4
num - 2        3
num - 1        2
```

It goes from `2` to `num - 1`, and the numbers on the side always add up to `num + 1`.

As for how many spaces you should print in between, you can first calculate the width of the entire rectangle. First count how many numbers there needs to be, add one for each space that follows each number (there are `num - 1` spaces in total). Finally, add one for each two digit number, because they need an extra space.

```
int rectangleWidth;
rectangleWidth = num * 2 - 1;
if (num &gt;= 10) {
    rectangleWidth += num - 9; // num - 9 is how many two digit numbers there are
}
```

The number of empty spaces to print is the rectangle&#39;s width minus the number of digits of the number on the left. You can further subtract the number of digits of the number on the right from this, so that the number on the right aligns.

```
for (int i = 2 ; i &lt;= num - 1 ; i++) {
    int left = i;
    int right = num + 1 - i;
    int emptyCount = rectangleWidth - (left &gt; 9 ? 2 : 1) - (right &gt; 9 ? 2 : 1);
    System.out.print(left);
    System.out.print(&quot; &quot;.repeat(emptyCount));
    System.out.println(right);
}
```

Finally, the last row is the numbers going in decreasing order. Note that the last row should only exist if `num &gt; 1`. The middle rows should only exist if `num &gt; 2`, but we already encoded that in the stopping condition of the loop `i &lt;= num - 1`.

```
if (num &gt; 1) {
    for (int i = num; i &gt;= 1; i--) {
        System.out.print(i + &quot; &quot;);
    }
    System.out.println();
}
```

