I guess you made it `final` because you want to prevent other classes from extending `RainOnTrees`. As [Effective Java][1] suggests (item 15), there&#39;s another way to keep a class close for extension without making it `final`:

1. Remove the `final` keyword;

2. Make its constructor `private`. No class will be able to extend it because it won&#39;t be able to call the `super` constructor;

3. Create a static factory method to instantiate your class.
    
        // No more final keyword here.
